    ("What is a rational expression?", "A rational expression is a fraction where numerator and/or denominator are polynomials.\n\nExamples:\n- (x+1)/(x-2)\n- (3x²+2x)/(x²-4)\n- 5/(x+3)\n\nKey rule: The denominator cannot be zero!\n(x+1)/(x-2) is undefined at x = 2\n\nSimplifying: Factor and cancel common factors\n(x²-4)/(x+2) = (x-2)(x+2)/(x+2) = x-2 (for x ≠ -2)\n\nOperations:\n- Multiply: (a/b) × (c/d) = (ac)/(bd)\n- Divide: (a/b) ÷ (c/d) = (a/b) × (d/c) = (ad)/(bc)\n- Add: Find common denominator, then add numerators\n  a/b + c/d = (ad + bc)/(bd)\n\nDomain restrictions: Set each denominator factor to zero and exclude those x-values.", "algebra", 3),
    ("What is the difference between an equation and an expression?", "Expression: A combination of numbers, variables, and operations (no equals sign)\n- 3x + 5\n- x² - 4\n- 2(x + 1)\n\nYou can simplify expressions, but you can't solve them.\n\nEquation: A statement that two expressions are equal (has an equals sign)\n- 3x + 5 = 14\n- x² - 4 = 0\n- 2(x + 1) = 10\n\nYou can solve equations (find the values of x that make it true).\n\nAnalogy:\n- Expression: '3x + 5' is like a recipe — you can evaluate it for any x\n- Equation: '3x + 5 = 14' is like a question — for what x is this true?\n\nInequality: Like an equation but with <, >, ≤, ≥\n- 3x + 5 > 14 (x > 3)\n\nFunction: An expression with a name\n- f(x) = 3x + 5 (assigns exactly one output to each input)", "algebra", 1),
    ("How do you factor a quadratic?", "For ax² + bx + c, find two numbers that:\n- Multiply to ac\n- Add to b\n\nExample: x² + 5x + 6\nNeed: two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to 5\n2 × 3 = 6 and 2 + 3 = 5\nx² + 5x + 6 = (x + 2)(x + 3)\n\nExample: x² - 7x + 12\nNeed: multiply to 12, add to -7\n-3 × -4 = 12 and -3 + -4 = -7\nx² - 7x + 12 = (x - 3)(x - 4)\n\nWhen a ≠ 1: 2x² + 7x + 3\nNeed: multiply to 2×3 = 6, add to 7\n1 × 6 = 6 and 1 + 6 = 7\nSplit: 2x² + x + 6x + 3\nGroup: x(2x + 1) + 3(2x + 1)\nFactor: (2x + 1)(x + 3)\n\nIf factoring doesn't work cleanly → use the quadratic formula\nAlways check: expand your answer to verify!", "algebra", 2),
    ("What is the difference between domain and range?", "Domain: All possible INPUT values (x-values)\nRange: All possible OUTPUT values (y-values)\n\nFor f(x) = x²:\n- Domain: All real numbers (any x works)\n- Range: [0, ∞) (squares are never negative)\n\nFor f(x) = 1/x:\n- Domain: All reals except x = 0 (can't divide by zero)\n- Range: All reals except y = 0 (1/x never equals 0)\n\nFor f(x) = √x:\n- Domain: [0, ∞) (can't take square root of negative)\n- Range: [0, ∞) (square root is never negative)\n\nFinding domain restrictions:\n1. Denominator ≠ 0\n2. Square root of non-negative\n3. Logarithm of positive numbers only\n\nInterval notation:\n- All reals: (-∞, ∞)\n- x > 3: (3, ∞)\n- x ≤ 5: (-∞, 5]\n- 0 < x ≤ 10: (0, 10]", "algebra", 2),

