    ("What is the cell cycle?", "The cell cycle is the sequence of events from one cell division to the next.\n\nInterphase (90% of the cycle):\n1. G1 (Gap 1): Cell grows, makes proteins, does its job\n2. S (Synthesis): DNA is replicated (each chromosome → 2 sister chromatids)\n3. G2 (Gap 2): Cell prepares for division (more growth, checks DNA)\n\nM Phase (10%):\n4. Mitosis: Nuclear division (PMAT)\n5. Cytokinesis: Cytoplasm divides, two daughter cells form\n\nCheckpoints:\n- G1 checkpoint: Is the cell big enough? Is DNA damaged? → Go or G0 (resting)\n- G2 checkpoint: Is DNA fully replicated? Any damage?\n- M checkpoint: Are chromosomes properly aligned?\n\nIf checkpoints fail → cancer (uncontrolled cell division)\nG0 phase: Cells that aren't dividing (neurons, muscle cells). Some can re-enter G1, others are stuck permanently.", "biology", 3),
    ("What is the difference between mRNA, tRNA, and rRNA?", "mRNA (messenger RNA):\n- Carries genetic code from DNA to ribosome\n- Made during transcription\n- Contains codons (3-base sequences that specify amino acids)\n- Short-lived, degraded after translation\n- Start codon: AUG, Stop codons: UAA, UAG, UGA\n\ntRNA (transfer RNA):\n- Delivers amino acids to the ribosome\n- Has an anticodon that matches mRNA codon (complementary)\n- Cloverleaf shape, L-shaped 3D structure\n- Each tRNA carries one specific amino acid\n- Example: tRNA with anticodon UAC carries Methionine\n\nrRNA (ribosomal RNA):\n- Structural and catalytic component of ribosomes\n- Ribosome = rRNA + proteins\n- Peptidyl transferase (makes peptide bonds) is a ribozyme (RNA enzyme)\n- Most abundant RNA type (~80% of cellular RNA)\n- Eukaryotic: 80S ribosome (60S + 40S subunits)\n- Prokaryotic: 70S ribosome (50S + 30S subunits)\n\nThe ribosome reads mRNA, tRNA brings amino acids, rRNA catalyzes bond formation. Together they make proteins.", "biology", 2),

